#Summary of Work Done

This project successfully designed, implemented, and evaluated a Home-Based Security Operations Center (SOC) for real-time threat detection,
visualization, and MITRE ATT&CK correlation using the ELK Stack. The system was deployed in a controlled virtualized environment, comprising
three virtual machines: a Kali Linux, a Windows 10 victim, and an Ubuntu Server hosting the ELK Stack. These machines were interconnected
via a private network, ensuring isolated communication for controlled attack simulations and log collection.

The ELK Stack, consisting of Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana, was utilized to process, store, and visualize logs generated during 
simulated attacks, which were executed using tools like Atomic Red Team and Metasploit. The system effectively detected a variety of attack
techniques, including brute force attacks (using Hydra), credential dumping, and PowerShell-based activity, with real-time alerts generated
for each event. Custom detection rules tailored to specific attack vectors proved effective, minimizing false positives.

Performance analysis demonstrated the SOC's real-time monitoring capabilities, with alerts generated almost instantaneously. The system’s 
granular logging and visualization in Kibana provided detailed insights, which are valuable for forensic analysis and incident
response.

The findings validate that a home-based SOC using open-source tools like the ELK Stack and attack simulation tools provides an effective, 
cost-efficient solution for real-time threat detection, making it suitable for small organizations or educational environments.
